\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {9}{\ignorespaces Stadium pipeline with unit-disk target. Red dots in (\subref  {fig:stadium-clean}) and (\subref  {fig:stadium-tutte}) mark the four curvature-transition points $(\pm a, \pm b)$ where the straight sides meet the semicircles (the stadium boundary is $C^1$ smooth there, not cornered---these are curvature-discontinuity points that would anchor any sliding parameterization). Row\nobreakspace  {}1: physical stadium with the right end-cap highlighted for tracking. Row\nobreakspace  {}2: no-shape-opt path (Tutte directly into Winslow). Row\nobreakspace  {}3: with-shape-opt path (Tutte $\to $ shape-opt $\to $ Winslow). Both paths produce valid, well-shaped stadium meshes and are nearly indistinguishable---on a convex smooth domain Winslow's bounded-distortion map does most of the work and shape-opt is a modest polish.\relax }}{15}{figure.caption.12}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:stadium-pipeline}{{9}{15}{Stadium pipeline with unit-disk target. Red dots in (\subref {fig:stadium-clean}) and (\subref {fig:stadium-tutte}) mark the four curvature-transition points $(\pm a, \pm b)$ where the straight sides meet the semicircles (the stadium boundary is $C^1$ smooth there, not cornered---these are curvature-discontinuity points that would anchor any sliding parameterization). Row~1: physical stadium with the right end-cap highlighted for tracking. Row~2: no-shape-opt path (Tutte directly into Winslow). Row~3: with-shape-opt path (Tutte $\to $ shape-opt $\to $ Winslow). Both paths produce valid, well-shaped stadium meshes and are nearly indistinguishable---on a convex smooth domain Winslow's bounded-distortion map does most of the work and shape-opt is a modest polish.\relax }{figure.caption.12}{}}
